originalText.text: I was part of the Tamron Hall Show on Thursday February 1st. Everyone from security to Tamron Hall herself were absolutely amazing and kind.

text.text: I was part of the Tamron Hall Show on Thursday February 1st. Everyone from security to Tamron Hall herself were absolutely amazing and kind.

originalText.text: My Sister and I went to a live taping of the view. It was very organized and we loved the whole experience. We also met some really cool people.

text.text: My Sister and I went to a live taping of the view. It was very organized and we loved the whole experience. We also met some really cool people.

originalText.text: Lining up outside you need to dress for weather. Then once inside building you stand in a cold windy hallway. There is a rest room at end  of hall. With a cooler of water and paper cups. I was seated behind a camera so never saw Whoopie unless I watched what the camera was showing. I really liked the warm up comic and she kept us laughing. Happy to see Ed Helm and Mark Harmon.  I will try for tickets again. Was fun.

originalText.text: Went for a taping of The View, and had a blast, you can see us, we were couple #3 in the "Kissing Booth" segment. We had our own time on national TV. We also got to see them tape a Star Trek Picard special. Seeing the New Generation crew was cool.

text.text: Went for a taping of The View, and had a blast, you can see us, we were couple #3 in the "Kissing Booth" segment. We had our own time on national TV. We also got to see them tape a Star Trek Picard special. Seeing the New Generation crew was cool.

originalText.text:
Going to watch The View, the production team instructed us, rather sternly, (after waiting outside in rather frigid New York winter morning air for quite awhile) to stay in our already-formed single-file line, and to get as close to each other as we could — two-by-two, if we wouldn’t mind; “That’d be great, thanks” — so as to make enough room so everyone in line could enter the building at the same time. Once inside, the long hallway we stood in offered less room for us to spread out a bit and get out of one another’s personal space…. yet we were constantly squeezing back up against each other every few seconds each time workers of the many active studios came rushing through the hallway,  most of them carrying equipment, pushing carts, or even navigating through the hallway with vehicles and six-foot-tall appliances and who-knows-whats on wheels!  It felt like it could have been better planned, or executed in a way to decrease the discomfort of us, the studios’ visitors.
I just feel like somebody, by now — considering how long the show has been on air, and how long guests have been visiting the studio to fill the seats so the show actually has a  ‘live studio audience’  in front of which to do the show — SOMEBODY  should take a look at that situation…and that if they haven’t, then they really ought to.

That’s why ‘4 Stars.’  I
